  "local_port": 48896,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are examples of prefixes and suffixes?",
  "response": "Prefixes and suffixes are groups of letters added to the beginning (prefix) or end (suffix) of a root word to change its meaning or grammatical function. Here are some examples:\n\n### **Examples of Prefixes:**\n1. **Un-** (not)  \n   - Example: *happy* \u2192 *unhappy* (not happy)  \n2. **Re-** (again)  \n   - Example: *do* \u2192 *redo* (do again)  \n3. **Pre-** (before)  \n   - Example: *heat* \u2192 *preheat* (heat before)  \n4. **Mis-** (wrongly)  \n   - Example: *understand* \u2192 *misunderstand* (understand wrongly)  \n5. **Dis-** (not, opposite)  \n   - Example: *agree* \u2192 *disagree* (not agree)  \n6. **In-** or **Im-** (not)  \n   - Example: *possible* \u2192 *impossible* (not possible)  \n7. **Over-** (too much)  \n   - Example: *cook* \u2192 *overcook* (cook too much)  \n8. **Sub-** (under)  \n   - Example: *marine* \u2192 *submarine* (underwater)  \n9. **Super-** (above, beyond)  \n   - Example: *natural* \u2192 *supernatural* (beyond natural)  \n10. **Bi-** (two)  \n    - Example: *cycle* \u2192 *bicycle* (two wheels)  \n\n### **Examples of Suffixes:**\n1. **-ly** (in a certain way)  \n   - Example: *quick* \u2192 *quickly* (in a quick way)  \n2. **-able** or **-ible** (able to be)  \n   - Example: *read* \u2192 *readable* (able to be read)  \n3. **-less** (without)  \n   - Example: *hope* \u2192 *hopeless* (without hope)  \n4. **-ful** (full of)  \n   - Example: *joy* \u2192 *joyful* (full of joy)  \n5. **-ness** (state of being)  \n   - Example: *happy* \u2192 *happiness* (state of being happy)  \n6. **-ment** (action or result)  \n   - Example: *move* \u2192 *movement* (the act of moving)  \n7. **-er** or **-or** (one who does)  \n   - Example: *teach* \u2192 *teacher* (one who teaches)  \n8. **-est** (superlative form)  \n   - Example: *fast* \u2192 *fastest* (the most fast)  \n9. **-ing** (present participle)  \n   - Example: *run* \u2192 *running* (in the act of running)  \n10. **-ed** (past tense)  \n    - Example: *walk* \u2192 *walked* (walked in the past)  \n\nThese prefixes and suffixes are widely used in English to modify the meaning or grammatical role of words.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
